crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects the presence of a number of Windows API functionality often seen within embedded executables. When this signature alerts on an executable, it is not an indication of malicious behavior. However, if seen firing in other file types, deeper investigation may be warranted.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB pie executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, BuildID[sha1]=4a355ae9393cebd8f4577cb2dfe524a8d964f6a2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.32, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is identified as the JetBrains Remote Development server launcher, written in Rust. This is evident from numerous strings such as `Usage: ./remote-dev-server`, `plugins/remote-dev-server/selfcontained/`, and `jbr/lib/fonts`. Its functionality involves setting up a Java Virtual Machine (JVM) environment, indicated by strings like `[JVM] Creating JVM`, `-agentlib:jdwp`, and `JDK_HOME`. The program also attempts to display graphical error messages using tools like `kdialog` and references the legitimate JetBrains support URL `https://jb.gg/ide/critical-startup-errors`. All observed behaviors are consistent with a legitimate remote development tool.
